"Puckrin E., Evans W.F.J., Adamson T.A.B.","Measurement of tropospheric ozone by thermal emission spectroscopy",1996,"Atmospheric Environment","30","4",,"563","568",,,10.1016/1352-2310(95)00319-3,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0029656698&partnerID=40&md5=aeed80cdb1073a263bd908adbb9942c8","Trent University, Environmental Resource Studies, Peterborough, Ont. K9J 7B8, Canada; Consumers Gas, Environmental Research and Analysis, North York, Ont. M2J 5C2, Canada","Puckrin, E., Trent University, Environmental Resource Studies, Peterborough, Ont. K9J 7B8, Canada; Evans, W.F.J., Trent University, Environmental Resource Studies, Peterborough, Ont. K9J 7B8, Canada; Adamson, T.A.B., Consumers Gas, Environmental Research and Analysis, North York, Ont. M2J 5C2, Canada","A new technique has been developed for the remote sensing of tropospheric ozone. In this technique the thermal radiation from ozone is measured against the cold background blackbody emission of clouds using ground-based FTIR spectroscopy. Preliminary measurements obtained in the springtime at Peterborough, Ontario, using this new technique, have indicated an average tropospheric ozone mixing ratio of 50 ± 7 ppbv within a 2.7 km layer from the surface for air flowing from a heavily industrialized and highly urbanized region. Ozone concentrations of this magnitude are in accordance with the amounts obtained for moderately polluted, springtime air using traditional in situ measurement techniques. The greenhouse radiation flux associated with this amount of ozone was estimated to be 0.61 W m-2 ± 13%. Since there are few techniques available for the remote sensing of tropospheric air pollutants, this new technique could be a potentially valuable development.","Air pollution; Global warming; Remote sensing; Thermal emission; Tropospheric ozone","ozone; air pollution; article; canada; industrialization; priority journal; remote sensing; spectroscopy; thermal conductivity; troposphere; urban area; ozone; ozone measurement; remote sensing; thermal emission spectroscopy; troposphere; Canada; Canada, Ontario, Peterborough; Ozone; Remote Sensing; Spectroscopy; Thermal Emissions; Tropospheric",,"ozone, 10028-15-6",,,,"Anderson, B.E., Gregory, G.L., Barrick, J.D.W., Collins J.E., Jr., Sachse, G.W., Shipham, M.C., Hudgins, C.H., Summertime tropospheric ozone distributions over central and eastern Canada (1994) J. Geophys. Res., 99, pp. 1781-1792; Chung, Y.S., Ground-level ozone and regional transport of air pollutants (1977) J. Appl. Met., 16, pp. 1127-1136; Clough, S.A., Kneizys, F.X., Anderson, G.P., Shettle, E.P., Chetwynd, J.H., Abreu, L.W., Hall, L.A., (1988) IRS '88: Current Problems in Atmospheric Radiation, pp. 372-375. , (edited by Lenoble J. and Geleyn J. F.), A. Deepak Publishing, Hampton, Virginia; Dickinson, R.E., Cicerone, R.J., Future global warming from atmospheric trace gases (1986) Nature, 319, pp. 109-115; Evans, W.F.J., Puckrin, E., An observation of the atmospheric thermal emission spectrum of trichlorofluoromethane (1994) Geophys. Res. Lett., 21, pp. 2381-2384; Evans, W.F.J., Puckrin, E., Observation of the atmospheric thermal emission spectrum of dichlorodifluoro-methane (1994) Can. J. Appl. Spectrosc., 39, pp. 85-90; Fishman, J., The global consequences of increasing tropospheric ozone concentrations (1991) Chemosphere, 22, pp. 685-695; Fishman, J., Ramanathan, V., Crutzen, P.J., Liu, S.C., Tropospheric ozone and climate (1979) Nature, 282, pp. 818-820; Hauglustaine, D.A., Granier, C., Brasseur, G.P., Megie, G., The importance of atmospheric chemistry in the calculation of radiative forcing on the climate system (1994) J. Geophys. Res., 99, pp. 1173-1186; Heidorn, K.C., Yap, D., A synoptic climatology for surface ozone concentrations in southern Ontario, 1976-1981 (1986) Atmospheric Environment, 20, pp. 695-703; Houghton, J.T., Callander, B.A., Varney, S.K., (1992) Supplementary Report to the IPCC Scientific Assessment, , Cambridge University Pr